post_text:
BUS TRANSPORTATION INFORMATION:
If you have an incoming 6th grader or 9th grader and you are planning for them to ride the bus to and from school, make sure you register your plans at https://www.wanee.org/TransportationRequestForms.aspx
Choose only one morning stop and one afternoon stop.

Bus routes will be done next week. This is your last chance to reserve a seat. Do not register for the school bus if you are starting the year as a remote learner.

Also, if any student moved or changed plans, you also need to register.
Bus routes and times will be published via an APP called StopFinder this year. Look for an email the first week of August. Be sure to keep your email address updated via your Skyward portal.

We are excited to get on the road again!!

Wa-Nee Parents-

If you plan to enroll a child in Remote Learning, please complete your child’s registration via Skyward and select Remote Learning by the end of the day on Friday, July 24, 2020.

If you have any questions, please feel welcome to contact my office at the number below.

Thank you,

Scot D. Croner, PhD
Superintendent
Wa-Nee Community Schools
(574)773-3131

shared_text:
NorthWood Yearbook
April 27 at 5:18 PM ·

Looking for a way to provide a little bit of "normal" for the class of 2020? Why not buy a copy of the 2020 Logue yearbook for a deserving senior?

Starting today, we're taking donations of yearbooks for seniors. On May 15, we will begin to pair these donated books with a senior who may not be able to otherwise afford copy of his or her senior yearbook.

To donate, visit shop.jostens.com and search for "NorthWood High School." When prompted, enter "Senior" for the first name and "Donation" for the last name. The current cost of the book is $75.

We are still in the process of completing the book, so coverage will include a special features on our time of remote learning, social distancing, and ways we are trying to continue to make this year special for our seniors.

If you know of a deserving senior who would like to receive a book donated through this process, email rbilinski@wanee.org.

post_text: Congratulations to our Wa-Nee Robotics teams!
shared_text:
Wa-Nee Robotics
March 8 at 1:47 AM ·

To summarize today’s Indiana State Championship: Wa-Nee absolutely dominated.

Indiana has (by far) more teams than any other state (or country) in the entire world. And only 5% of those Indiana teams have the honor of advancing to the World Championship next month.

Not Wa-Nee, though. 43% of our teams advanced and have the privilege of competing against the world’s best! Forty. Three. Percent.

What a great showing today! Wa-Nee Robotics just cemented themselves as one of the premiere robotics programs in all of Indiana.

post_text: What a great event. We are extremely proud of all of our students and coaches. Good luck to all as we enter tournament season!
shared_text:
Wa-Nee Robotics
February 21 at 2:06 AM ·

It was a FULL HOUSE at Woodview Elementary tonight for the NIBL Finals. We had more people than seats, but that's alright! We want to thank all the families, teachers, staff, and the rest of the community for coming out to support our future engineers!

That being said, congratulations to:

15294A (Eaglebots Red) for bringing home the Skills Champion Award, putting up a score of 167 that ranks them 25th in the world (out of nearly 6,000 teams)!

85974B (NWMS Panthers) and 15294B (Eaglebots Blue) for winning the Teamwork Championship with a score of 112!

64535C (Nappanee Bulldogs #3) for winning the Most Improved Award by growing over 51 points since Session 1!

Well done to ALL students and coaches for making the NIBL one of the premiere leagues in all of Indiana!! On to State!!

post_text: Way to go Wakarusa Elementary and Wa-Nee Robotics!
shared_text:
Wa-Nee Robotics
January 11 at 10:10 PM ·

Two days ago, the REC Foundation called with a need to fill the Lakeland Intermediate competition in LaGrange. There weren’t enough teams for it to be a state-qualifying event.

So, Wakarusa stepped up at the very last second! And despite the majority of the teams being middle school teams, Wakarusa Elementary represented Wa-Nee well in their first competition of the season!

-32116C finished the teamwork matches in 1st.
-32116A finished in 4th.
-32116M finished in 11th, just missing the Finals.

Despite not qualifying for State (lost by only 3 points in the Finals), they were able to bring home the Judges Award, given to the team deserving of special recognition. Well done Coach Protzman, Coach Jenkins, and all Wildcats!

post_text:
Another great show of sportsmanship, this time by our NLC Champion Volleyball team. This is what "winning" is all about.

"I had a chance to witness sportsmanship at the NW vs. WHS volleyball match on 10-10-2019.

It was Senior night at Wawasee and after the 6 Sr. Athletes were honored and announced, for several more minutes the celebration was extended as the Sr players were greeted by teammates and parents. on the Wawasee sideline.

The Northwood players waited until the Sr Celebration was complete before starting any warm-up and by so doing showed respect. I noticed this was initiated by NW players and the team waited until the celebration was complete.

Probably un-noticed to many in attendance, but a little thing displayed by a group of NW student athletes to wait until the Sr. festivities were complete.

Nicely Done Northwood Volleyball players, program and students."

--Mr. Tim Yoder

post_text: Congratulations to our Woodview Eaglebots! The 2019 World Robotics Excellence Award winners!
shared_text:
Jake Simons is with David Vincent and 20 others.
April 30, 2019 at 11:49 PM ·

-7 billion people on earth.
-6,000 elementary robotics teams in the world.
-410 qualify for the World Championship.
-40 countries represented.
-1 Excellence Award winner, the highest possible honor, given to the top overall organization in the world.....

And that team is from small-town Nappanee, Indiana!!!! Your Woodview Eaglebots!!!!

Oh, and Blue Team was Division World Champs, and 6th OVERALL IN THE WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP FINALS!!!!!

Oh, and Red Team finished 2nd in their Division after a record-setting tiebreaker....and TIED FOR 2nd IN THE WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP FINALS!!!!!

I am absolutely stunned! Blown away! Where do we go from here?!?! I’ve never been more proud in my life. I already knew these kids were going to be world changers someday....I’m just so grateful to be a small part in their magical journey this year!

#GoEaglebots
#BeatChina
#WeDid
